Reason: The issue with your code is that it's currently only checking for 'example.com' in the path variable provided by flask route, while it should also check if there exists 'http://example.com', or 'https://example.com' as a part of URL parameter before performing redirection or returning error message respectively. To cater this requirement I have changed the `<url>` to `<path:url>` in your @app.route decorator which means Flask will treat the segment after /redirect/ as a path and it can include slashes (/).

